{"type":"assistant.message","data":{"messageId":"a8c8ed05-ecf2-4e3d-a7e7-edcd5dba2e73","content":"","toolRequests":[{"toolCallId":"tooluse_Lyw89TEits0f6IzuLxDQQv","name":"bash","arguments":{"command":"cd /tmp/sv-ea2fc82b74fb4af58c05f698e37f71ad && dotnet --version 2>/dev/null && echo \"---\" && dotnet --list-sdks 2>/dev/null | tail -3","description":"Check dotnet SDK version","initial_wait":10},"type":"function","intentionSummary":"Check dotnet SDK version"}],"interactionId":"3c2d4835-0b9c-4bfc-9c41-2fc35661cfa4","reasoningOpaque":"","reasoningText":"The developer report describes a common issue: `dotnet build` from the CLI is slow for incremental builds (2-4 seconds even with no changes), while Visual Studio rebuilds nearly instantly. The root cause is well-known:\n\n**Why Visual Studio is faster:** VS uses a long-lived MSBuild server process (the \"design-time build\" process) that keeps the project graph and MSBuild nodes in memory. When you hit build, it reuses those warm nodes — no process startup, no re-evaluation of the project XML.\n\n**Why `dotnet build` is slower:** Each `dotnet build` invocation starts a new MSBuild process, evaluates the project files from scratch, and then determines that nothing needs to be built. \n\nThe 2-4 second overhead comes from spinning up a fresh process and re-evaluating the project structure. I'm considering a few approaches: .NET 8+ has MSBuild server support enabled by default, but the developer might still be experiencing slowness if it's not fully helping or is somehow disabled. Using `dotnet watch` would keep a persistent process running that detects file changes and rebuilds automatically, which would give the closest CLI equivalent to the Visual Studio experience. There are other options worth exploring too.\n\nThe most practical recommendations are using `dotnet watch build` to maintain a long-running process that watches for changes and rebuilds incrementally—this is ideal for the edit-build-test cycle. I should also suggest `dotnet build --no-restore` to skip the NuGet restore phase on every build, since that adds overhead even when nothing has changed. Finally, ensuring the MSBuild server is properly enabled would help with process reuse. I should verify that `dotnet` is installed and then run a quick test to show the performance difference between a standard build and one with these optimizations applied.","outputTokens":903,"requestId":"040D:37135:44DADA:5026F3:69F00420"},"id":"cf117a40-a79f-44fb-81d7-ebd0c8262df6","timestamp":"2026-04-28T00:49:55.818Z","parentId":"528a39c4-8d1c-4d28-bb33-4d8b7554664b"}
